  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Hawthorne sits in a stretch of Brisbane's inner east that buyers consistently return to. The suburb sits between Bulimba and Morningside, with river frontage to the north and a walkable connection to Oxford Street's cafes and restaurants. That combination of liveability, character housing stock, and school catchment access creates a buyer profile that is both motivated and competitive. If you are selling here, the fundamentals work in your favour, but that does not mean any campaign will do.</p>

      <p>Sellers in Hawthorne sometimes assume that demand will carry a property regardless of how it is presented or priced. The reality is more nuanced. A home that is well prepared, accurately priced, and properly marketed will consistently outperform one that is not, even in a strong market. The gap between a careful campaign and a careless one in this suburb can be substantial, and it tends to show up most clearly in the final negotiation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Hawthorne</h2>
      <p>The dominant buyer group in Hawthorne is families, typically with children in primary or secondary school, or approaching that stage. The catchment for Lourdes Hill College draws consistent demand from families seeking a foothold in the area before their daughters reach secondary age. Churchie's catchment similarly pulls Anglican families who want proximity to the school without a long commute. These are not casual buyers. They have often been watching the suburb for twelve months or more before they act, and when they move, they move decisively.</p>

      <p>The secondary buyer group is owner-occupier couples, either upsizing from an inner-city apartment or relocating from interstate with a clear idea of the lifestyle they want. Proximity to the CityCat, the walking and cycling paths along the river, and the density of good coffee within a short walk of most streets in Hawthorne is a genuine draw. These buyers tend to prioritise presentation and liveability over the purely functional. They respond well to a home that has been styled thoughtfully and feels ready to move into.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value here</h2>
      <p>River views and river access add meaningful premium to Hawthorne properties, particularly on streets north of Riding Road. Properties with a clear view, or those within a short walk of the river path, attract a different level of buyer attention than comparable homes further back. If your property has any aspect of river outlook, that needs to be communicated clearly in the marketing and photographed at the right time of day.</p>

      <p>Character integrity matters in Hawthorne more than in many suburbs. The pre-war homes, Queenslanders, and interwar bungalows in this area attract buyers who specifically want original features. Ornate fretwork, polished timber floors, and high ceilings are selling points rather than maintenance concerns for the right buyer. Extensive modern renovation that strips character out of a home can reduce appeal in this market, particularly if the execution is not high quality. Conversely, a sympathetically updated character home, where the original fabric has been retained and the kitchen and bathrooms have been improved without erasing the period feel, consistently performs well.</p>

      <p>Land size and the ability to extend or add a pool are factors buyers weigh carefully. Lots with north-facing rear aspects and enough depth to accommodate a pool are consistently in demand from family buyers who want to stay in the suburb long term. If your block has these attributes, they are worth highlighting in your sales strategy.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to prepare your home</h2>
      <p>The preparation steps that consistently produce the best results in Hawthorne are not complicated, but they require discipline. Start with the exterior. First impressions at the kerb matter in a suburb where buyers arrive having already formed opinions from online listings, and a tidy garden, freshly painted front fence, and clean driveway signal that the rest of the home has been looked after. Move through the interior and address any deferred maintenance before you list. Buyers in this price bracket conduct pest and building inspections, and a long defect list gives them leverage in negotiation that is hard to recover from.</p>

      <p>Styling makes a measurable difference to how quickly a property sells and to the final price. It is not about disguising the home. It is about helping buyers see how they would live in it. A Hawthorne buyer looking at a four-bedroom character home is imagining school mornings, weekend breakfasts, and summer afternoons in the backyard. The staging should support that picture without being so curated that it feels sterile.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pricing and campaign structure</h2>
      <p>Hawthorne's market has enough depth to support auction campaigns for quality family homes, particularly in the mid to upper price range. Auctions tend to work well when there are two or more buyers who have identified the property as a genuine target and are prepared to compete. If the buyer pool is likely to be narrower, a structured offers campaign or a private treaty with a clear price point can produce a better outcome. The right structure depends on the property, the price bracket, and what comparable sales suggest about buyer depth in the current market. That judgement call is worth having an honest conversation about before you commit to a campaign method.</p>

